It's technically "dual-rear-wheel", and if you must use American slang, it's "duallie", not "dually". The 'y' just looks silly and awkward, and makes it look like someone is "dually a wheel and a suspension component", i.e. "both" (not to be confused with "duly"). And it is NOT "the plural of dual", as I've seen at least one person state! That would be "duals". The only grammatical terms are "dual" and "dual-rear-wheel". "Dually" suggests an object is "dually a lawyer and a thief", and is wrong.
